CLINICAL HISTORY:  55 year old male with headache and syncope.
MEDICATIONS:  N/A
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by increase in beta and decrease in alpha. Hyperventilation does not activate the record. Photic stimulation elicits brief driving.
HR:	80 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No focal nor epileptiform features are observed in this study.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	22 year old right handed woman with severe asthma and episodes of right sided shaking, trembling, loss of consciousness, and incontinence. These have occurred in clusters for the past 2 years.
MEDICATIONS:  Albuterol, Prednisone,  Primacort.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. Photic stimulation elicits driving. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background. Drowsiness increases the synchronicity of the record.
HR: 	60-70 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No focal nor epileptiform features are observed.  Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   48 year old male with a history of tremor during sleep which began in July 2009.  The patient has a history of an MVA in June 2009 and hypertension.
MEDICATIONS:  Valtrex, Nexium, Singulair, Metoprolol, Verapamil, Furosemide, Doxazosin, Flax seed oil, Omega fish oil.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a low-voltage but wellÂ­ defined 10 Hz alpha rhythm which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Features of drowsiness include an increase of beta.  Hyperventilation produces background slowing.  Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORR ELATION:  No epileptiform features are observed.  Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy, and a low-voltage pattern is a normal finding.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   59 year old right handed female with headaches and sharp occipital pain.

MEDICATIONS: None

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is awake for most of the study, however, is in and out of drowsiness.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG shows a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm with 25 mV.  In addition, when drowsy the patient has 5 Hz temporal waves and some vertex waves.  Also noted is a rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness (RMTD) which is a normal variant, entered during photic stimulation.  The patient is seen to have driving at 7 Hz.



HR  :


84 bpm with occasional PVCs when drowsy.



IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy  Clinical evaluation of PVCs in sleep may be valuable.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 88 year old woman with frequent falling, rolled out of bed and
developed a new subdural now on the right.
MEDICATIONS: Simvastatin, verapamil, Keppra, Xalatan
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20
system of electrodes placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake and briefly
drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is low
voltage. There is a defined 8 to 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. Features of
drowsiness including increase in background slowing. Because of the trauma, there is
some electrode artifact. Features of drowsiness including increase in background beta.
HR: 72 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. Despite the
history of recurrent subdural hematomas, there are no epileptiform features noted.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  78 year old right handed female who has a history of strokes in
2007 with subsequent seizures. She was complaining of lightheadedness. She denied any further seizure activity since 2007.

MEDICATIONS:  Citalopram, Enalapril, Atenolol, Lovastatin, Aggrenox, Roxicet, hydrochlorothiazide, Glipizide, Oxycodone

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF  THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage, but there is 9.5 hertz symmetric reactive alpha rhythm. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta. Rare, isolated right or left temporal theta/delta is noted in drowsiness.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.

HR:	66 bpm


IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.


CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No epileptiform features were noted. A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy, but at present, the patient is symptom free off
seizure medications.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 60 year old right handed woman with epilepsy, last seizure August 2009.
MEDICATIONS: Carbatrol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low-voltage, frontocentral beta. Hyperventilation is performed early in the record producing a small amount of theta. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.

IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 23 year old right handed male, with new onset tonic clonic
seizures in May and November, total of 3 seizures.
MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation and completed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz 30 microvolt
posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta, followed
by POSTS, and vertex waves. Hyperventilation does not significantly activate the
record. Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed. Additional EEG
recording may be helpful to characterize this individual's epilepsy.

amplitude with a 20-30 microvolt 10 hertz alpha rhythm and a amount of low

CLINICAL HISTORY: 55 year old right handed male with new onset seizures, following
right sided stroke in December, 2008, seizure free since April, 2009, but two seizures
with postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Unknown.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic simulation was
performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively
low-voltage, for an adult of this age, but quite well organized, with generous beta and a
glimpse of an alpha rhythm. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta activity
as well as a small amount of delta. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
Beta spindles are observed in stage 2 sleep.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features are observed. Normal. EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.2 hertz posterior

Ã¡ amount of age related changes including shifting temporal theta is observed.
Hyperventilation does not activate the records. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 77 year old male with past history of epilepsy, now with a lung mass and a syncopal episode.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Serax, ASA, Protonix, Lisinopril, Norvasc, Thiamine, Folic Acid
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm. In the transition to drowsiness there is occasional theta identified independently in the left or right mid to anterior temporal region. Deeper stages of sleep are not identified. Photic stimulation elicits a subtle driving response.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The temporal changes described, left greater than right, in transition to sleep are considered normal for a subject of this age. There were no epileptiform features.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 47 year old male with paroxysmal episodes which can be
triggered by a hot beverage characterized by repetitive sneezing, confusion, weakness,
sweating and even loss of consciousness.

MEDICATIONS: None.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a
10.7 hertz alpha rhythm of 40 microvolts with a small amount of low voltage,
frontocentral beta activity. Features of drowsiness include rhythmic background slowing
with vertex were in stage 1 sleep followed by arousals. Hyperventilation increases the
amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation elicits supraharmonic driving.

HR: 68 bpm

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. If there are any concerns, a repeat
study capturing one of his paroxysmal sneezing spells is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 44 year old male with first ever seizure 2/20/2010.
MEDICATIONS: Albuterol

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic; simulation are completed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation produces rhythmic theta. Intermittently in drowsiness, there is some rhythmic left to right temporal theta but none that is specifically pathologic. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.

HR: 56 bpm

IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The previously described, sharply contoured in theta seen in the first study was not identified. There were some normal variants but nothing that was specifically epileptiform. If seizures recur, additional EEG recording may be valuable.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 44 year old female with epilepsy since age 19, with nocturnal tonic-clonic seizures with incontinence, hypertension, hyperlipidemia. Seizures were related to an assault at age 19.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Gabapentin, Remeron
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.3 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in background theta. There are occasional bursts of paroxysmal rhythmic slowing noted as the patient transitions from hyperventilation into stage I sleep. Brief epochs of paroxysmal slowing are noted as she transitions into sleep with vertex waves. The pattern is overall most reminiscent of hypnagogic hypersynchrony but there is a suggestion of asynchrony in the bursts. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The overall organization is acceptable. There is hypnagogic hypersynchrony which is at the limits of organization. In this individual with a history of epilepsy, additional EEG recordings may be valuable to delineate underlying epileptiform activity as well as to determine if there is an epileptiform discharge hidden in the hypnagogic hypersynchrony. Hypnagogic hypersynchrony, however, is a normal finding.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 18 year old with excessive jerking in sleep, evaluate for restless
leg syndrome.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well
organized with a 10.5 Hz, 40 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of
low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation produces an increase in
amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. Drowsiness is
characterized by slow rolling eye movements with the appearance of vertex waves in sleep.
HR: 55 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are identified. A normal EEG is
typically found in restless leg syndrome. If periodic leg movements of sleep are
suspected, a polysomnogram might be beneficial.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 45 year old right handed female with history of seizures. Patient states she had seizure like episode during sleep on 4/14/2010. She woke up tired and with a headache and confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Prozac.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm of 40-60 microvolts with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. Hyperventilation does not significantly activate the record.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed; however, a normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing capturing sleep is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 39 year old right handed female who is a lung transplant recipient admitted for pneumonia, she has uncontrollable jerks/shakiness. Patient has history of depression, spacing out, confusion, short term memory loss and headaches, childhood epilepsy.

MEDICATIONS: Celexa, Cellcept, Prednisone, Itraconazole, Nystatin, Warfarin, Fentanyl, Ambien, Neurontin

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is almost entirely asleep record. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. At some points, behaviorally, the patient appears to the technologist to be awake but the EEG suggests that she is sleepy.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The vast majority of this record demonstrates stage II sleep with vertex waves, spindles and K complexes. Brief eye opening with what seems to be an awake state is more compatible with a drowsy state followed quickly by the appearance of vertex activity. In this bedside portable record, there is some artifact and a little asymmetry seen intermittently at CZ/C4.

HR: 66 bpm

IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: Additional clinical information is important to determine the cause of the patient's excessive drowsiness. Because bf the artifact noted at CZ and C4, consider a repeat study in the lab is advised.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 25 year old right handed male with right-sided weakness and tingling.

MEDICATIONS: Tylenol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage but there is a 9 Hertz, 25 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing followed by POSTS. There is a significant section of the record with a drowsy pattern with slow rolling eye movements. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude with a background.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. This is a somewhat low voltage record but again is not necessarily indicative of pathology.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 49 year old right handed woman with epilepsy since 2002, last
seizure was 8 months ago with bilateral hand tremulousness with no recall of events.
History of pancreatitis and heart disease. Seizures are characterized by lack of
awareness, bizarre behavior, head banging and "ingestion of soap."
MEDICATIONS: Metoprolol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic simulation was
performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a well-organized 9.3 Hz, 50
microvolt, posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral
beta activity. Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm and
an increase in beta. Photic stimulation elicits a scant driving response at faster flash
frequencies.
HR: 96 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is the second normal EEG in the Temple database.
A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis. If this individual continues to have
frequent events, capturing an EEG with an in-or outpatient monitoring system may be
beneficial.

patient becomes drowsy there is a prominent in theta. Hyperventilation produces

HR: 60bpm

CLINICAL HISTORY: 50 year old right handed female who had a meningioma resected in 2002, with a seizure in 2005, after a seizure-free period of what may have been 5 years.
MEDICATIONS: Divalproex
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic simulation is performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a well-organized 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm. Mu rhythm is identified but testing is not performed to confirm this. Brief drowsiness is characterized by slow, rolling eye movements. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: EEGs in 2005 and in 2006 identified subtle left temporal slowing which was not identified today. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy and if further evaluation is needed, additional EEG recording capturing deeper stages of sleep may help identify epileptiform activity.

Clinical HISTORY: 76 year old male with sellar tumor, prostate cancer, CABG and seller mass.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Synthroid, Ativan, Acetaminophen, Zocor, Protonix, Zestril, Lovenox, Hydrocortisone, Percocet, Vancomycin, Cefepime

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is relatively somnolent. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is remarkable for generous beta and theta. Snare artifact is noted. As the patient drifts off to sleep, the muscle activity drops out and there is more of a beta with delta pattern. Slow spindle activity is noted. Stimulation of the patient is performed on 2 occasions and produces an increase in beta on one occasion and the other does not seem to awaken the patient at all.

HR: 80 bpm
IMPRESSION: A normal EEG due to:
1. Pattern of hypersomnolence.
2. Excess beta and theta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are identified. Clinical correlation may be important to determine why this individual is so sleepy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 28 year old right handed woman with migraine headaches, vomiting and a history of postpartum heart failure following delivery of a stillbirth infant. Left middle cerebral artery stenosis.
MEDICATIONS: Butalbital, Clonazepam, Celexa, Citalopram, Fexofenadine

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient is asleep during photic stimulation.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 12Hz alpha rhythm with generous, low voltage, frontocentral beta. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta with vertex waves, spindles and posts in stage II sleep. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 60 bpm

IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The generous beta identified in this record may be due to the use of benzodiazepines. No epileptiform features were noted.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 39 year old woman who had recent repair of lateral meniscus tear and an episode postoperatively of head deviation to the right and paroxysms for a few minutes with confusion. The patient has a history of VP shunt, blindness, and past seizure disorder.
MEDICATIONS: Unknown.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the postoperative care unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient initially appears to be still sedated postoperatively.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The initial sections of the record demonstrate a drowsy individual with a lower voltage, slower pattern. As she awakens, an 11 Hz alpha rhythm is identified bilaterally. Artifact is seen on the right compatible with prior craniotomy. As the recording continues, the patient is increasingly awake.
HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The initial sections of the record demonstrate a sedated pattern compatible with acute postoperative state, but by the end the patient is awake and there are no pathologic findings. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow up study in the lab maybe of use.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 61 year old right handed male with epilepsy, currently seizure free for 1 year.
MEDICATIONS: Phenytoin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This an awake stage 2 record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is an 11.7 Hz alpha rhythm which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening. There is a small amount of low voltage frontal central beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with K-complexes, vertex waves, spindles, and POSTS noted in stage 2 sleep. Hyperventilation does not activate the record. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response, despite the fact that the patient is following asleep.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were observed. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 32 year old right handed woman with a history of orthostatic
hypotension and usual episode 2 weeks ago while driving a car in which she had
numbness in both hands followed by lightheadedness, visual changes and then perioral
and right hand numbness. Past history of orthostatic hypotension. These symptoms
were followed by confusion and migraine headache.

MEDICATIONS: Prenatal Vit.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 1 0-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a
symmetric, reactive, 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage,
frontocentral beta activity. Both drowsiness and hyperventilation are associated with
slowing of the alpha rhythm to 8.5 Hz rhythmic paroxysmal mixed frontal theta and
delta. Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained but there are brief vertex waves.
Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.

HR: 60bpm

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. There is rhythmic
paroxysmal stowing identified in hyperventilation which Is an anticipated finding in a
fasting adult.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 60 year old right handed woman with recurrent syncope, past
history of tonic clonic seizures, heart attack, and hypertension.
MEDICATIONS: Quinapril, Procardia, Oxybutynin, isosorbide, ASA, Lovastatin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake through stage
II sleep. Photic stimulation is performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.8 Hz alpha rhythm with
a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity. The patient transitions rapidly
between wakefulness and stage II sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and
POSTS. On one occasion as she is transitioning in and out of stage II sleep, during
photic stimulation, it appears that there is new or alpha activity on the right, almost as
there are vertex waves and POSTS. Photic stimulation produces supraharmonic driving
responses which can be differentiated from the patient drifting in and out of sleep, and,
in fact, she has a harmonic that is unusual in that it sometimes to be 3 or 5 times the
frequency of flash stimuli.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 25 year old right handed woman with episodes which are described as spasms. They include eye fluttering, head rocking and crying. Her brother and her child both have epilepsy.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a symmetric, 11 Hz, 70 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces a great deal of blinking. Brief drowsiness is characterized by a small amount of theta and some bursts of rhythmic, hypnagogic hypersynchrony. Photic stimulation elicits abundant, symmetric driving. The patient has an event during photic stimulation characterized by frequent eye blink. The eye blink frequency increases after the photic stimulation stops. She has shaking of her legs and impaired responsiveness. This is followed by moaning. No epileptiform features are associated with these behaviors. The EEG demonstrates a normal awake pattern throughout these behaviors which began at 11:44. unfortunately, the camera is primarily on her face and upper body and this is the lower extremity activity. Afterward, the patient has intermittent arm shaking noted at 11:47, again difficult to see on the camera. Afterward she feels drained and tired but the EEG continues to demonstrate a normal awake pattern.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is the second EEG for this individual. During both EEGs, the patient had behaviors characteristic of nonepileptic seizures with characteristic behavior, crying in the absence of epileptiform activity.

Although deeper stages of sleep were not achieved, just as the patient was becoming drowsy there seems to be some subtle underlying 4-5 Hz theta in the left occipital region.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.
Photic stimulation elicited a bilateral driving response.
Heart:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  A very subtle abnormality was noted in this EEG just as the patient was becoming drowsy and included some focal theta in the left occipital parietal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  For this individual with a history of early developmental pathology and possible meningitis, these findings may relate to that premorbid process.  The findings were seen in a very
restricted section of the EEG.  If there is any questions, additional EEG recording may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  An 18 -year-old male with new onset tonic clonic seizures after development of a sore throat on March 14, 2013.

Photic stimulation did elicit a driving response.  Photic stimulation also served to alert the patient.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  This individual demonstrated excessive drowsiness, rapidly drifting into stage II sleep.  Clinical correlation is suggested.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  29 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 37-year-old woman with a history of 2 generalized tonic-clonic convulsions as well as an episode of staring, mumbling, speaking gibberish, not responding during the event.  The last event occurred approximately 3 weeks ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Zyrtec.
CONDITIONS OF THE RECORDING:  The recording is performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude 11-11.5 Hz activity that attenuates with eye opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitude anteriorly.  During sleep, POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep), and symmetrical sleep spindles are captured.  During hyperventilation, mild diffuse slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm was observed.  Photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.  There is a continuous EKG artifact.  There is diffuse excess beta activity.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
Stage II sleep.
Excess beta.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 29-minute EEG.  The lack of epileptiform discharges noted on the EEG does not preclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excess beta could be secondary to the medication effect such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  21 minutes.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10/20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was performed.  Photic stimulation was not performed.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 37-year-old man admitted on 05/14/2013 for loss of consciousness and generalized weakness.
MEDICATIONS:  Toradol, Percocet, oxycodone, Zofran, acyclovir.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated 9 to 9.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep, the posterior dominant rhythm attenuates.  Acute theta is present, and symmetrical vertex waves are observed.  Hyperventilation was performed with fair effort and produces no significant changes in the background.  Photic stimulation was not performed.
A regular heart rate is noted on a single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
No stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage II sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persists, a repeat study with stage II sleep may be of benefit.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 57-year-old woman, seizure free for 1-2 years.  Characteristics of seizures included oral automatisms and tongue biting, positive family history of epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, multivitamins, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This is a routine outpatient EEG with hyperventilation and photic stimulation.  Impedances were acceptable aside from the T1 and T2 electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  In relaxed wakefulness and early drowsiness, rhythmic midtemporal theta activity was noted with 5 Hz activity seen infrequently, left more so than the right.  Stage 2 sleep was captured at the close of the recording with vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  No temporal theta was noted at that time.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep, but produced vigorous bilateral driving response with supraharmonic driving.  Hyperventilation produced an increase in amplitude of the background.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness through brief stage 2 sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the third EEG for this subject which did not identify epileptiform activity.  The rhythmic midtemporal theta noted in drowsiness is a normal variant.
